 field. The essays are organized in five thematic groups covering a wide variety of issues of ancient Greek linguistics, ranging from epigraphy and the study of individual dialects to various other aspects of the structure of the language, such as phonetics and phonology, morphology, lexicon and word formation, etymology, metrics as well as many syntactic matters and problems of pragmatics and stylistics of the language; a number of essays move in the middle ground where language, linguistics and philology crosscut and cross-fertilize each other with the application of linguistic theory to the study of classical texts. The work is of special relevance to scholars interested in Greek linguistics in general and in particular aspects of the Greek language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGreek language. 0aGreek philology. 4aAltgriechisch. 4aGriechische Philologie. 4aHistorische Linguistik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greek language.  aGreek linguistics.  aGreek philology.  ahistorical linguistics.1 aAllan, Rutger J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrio Vega, María Luisa del, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedetti, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernabé, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlažek, Václav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBubenik, Vit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConti, Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConti, Luz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCuzzolin, Pierluigi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDardano, Paola, e